  "id": "019d31d8-81f8-7d30-acb6-271e187eb0dd",
  "content": "# Embedding Storage Format: Research Findings (2026-03-27)\n\n## Context\nAt 14,682 entries (232 MB), the JSON knowledge format stores embeddings as JSON float arrays — 92% of file size. Industry research and 5-persona architecture review conducted.\n\n## Key Findings\n\n### Industry Consensus\n- No production vector DB stores embeddings as JSON. All use raw binary (Qdrant: mmap flat files, ChromaDB: HNSWlib binary, Milvus: columnar segments, LanceDB: Lance format).\n- JSON float arrays are 3.3x larger than raw binary (10.3 KB vs 3.0 KB per 768-dim vector).\n- JSON serialization is 10-16x slower than binary formats (serde_json: 5,690us vs bincode: 459us vs bitcode: 360us).\n- For fixed-size f32 arrays, no serialization library needed — raw `bytemuck::cast_slice` is optimal.\n\n### Directory Sharding: Not Needed\n- UUIDv7 prefix sharding is broken — all 14,682 files start with `019` (timestamp in first 48 bits, `01` covers 2004-2039).\n- ext4 htree handles 100K files in one directory fine (readdir: 118ms, stat: 2ms).\n- Git operations on 14K files: all under 40ms. Sharding adds tree object overhead with no benefit.\n- Recommendation: defer sharding until 500K+ entries per scope.\n\n### Per-File Size Breakdown\n- Embedding JSON: ~10,257 bytes (92%)\n- Content: ~301 bytes avg (3%)\n- Metadata + structure: ~584 bytes (5%)\n- Stripping embeddings: 15 KB → ~1.2 KB per file\n\n### Scale Projections\n| Entries | Current JSON | After (JSON + binary sidecar) | Git-tracked |\n|---------|-------------|-------------------------------|-------------|\n| 14,682 | 232 MB | 18 MB + 43 MB = 61 MB | 18 MB |\n| 100,000 | 1.6 GB | 120 MB + 293 MB = 413 MB | 120 MB |\n\n## 5-Persona Review Blocking Issues\n1. No concurrency strategy for sidecar writes → piggyback on Redb write txn lock\n2. Header entry_count creates crash-safety gap → derive from file size (FAISS pattern)\n3. Tombstone-by-zeroing is fragile → use Redb as authoritative index, no tombstones in sidecar\n4. Compaction not atomic → write-then-rename pattern\n5. Migration must be two-phase → write sidecar first, strip JSON second\n6. No rollback path → preserve old read path for one major version\n7. Fresh clone broken post-migration → auto-detect + async re-embed on startup\n\n## Open Question\nSidecar-vs-Redb: Multiple reviewers (Senior SWE, PM) questioned whether a custom binary sidecar is necessary, or if vectors should just go in a dedicated Redb table. Tradeoff: Redb eliminates custom format/locking/compaction concerns but may be slower for sequential HNSW rebuild scans. Under investigation.",
  "source_version": "chore/dev-loop-knowledge-persistence",
